#week-title("Three", "The Metal Meditations: Sitting with Each Force")

=== Core Teaching

Direct experiential acquaintance with the seven metals is not supplementary to
the philosophical study — it is essential to it. The practitioner who has spent
time with each metal in meditative attention, attending to the quality of
awareness that each evokes, has developed a perceptual baseline that will
inform every subsequent metallic preparation. The metals are teachers in a
direct and immediate sense.

*Acquiring the metals.* The following sources are practical for each metal:
- *Gold:* A small gold coin, ring, or piece of jewellery. (Even 9-karat gold
  is adequate for meditative purposes.)
- *Silver:* A silver coin or piece of sterling silver jewellery.
- *Iron:* A clean iron nail, iron filing compacted into a small disc, or a
  cast-iron object.
- *Copper:* A piece of copper pipe, a copper coin, or copper sheet.
- *Quicksilver (Mercury):* Do not handle — it is toxic in all forms. Work
  with iron pyrite ("fool's gold") as a Mercury-kingdom stand-in for meditative
  purposes, attending to its mercurial quality of reflecting and scattering
  light.
- *Tin:* A piece of tin sheet, pewter (tin alloy), or solder.
- *Lead:* As noted in Week 2 — fishing weights, lead sheet. Always gloved.

*The protocol for each meditation.* Twenty minutes. Sit with the metal in
gloved hands (or ungloved for non-toxic metals). Attend to: its weight,
temperature, texture, visual quality (how it reflects or absorbs light), and
the quality of awareness or bodily sensation it evokes. Do not try to produce
an experience — simply attend and record.

*Sequence.* Work through the metals over two to three sessions, grouping them
by pillar: Pillar of Severity first (Saturn/Lead, Mars/Iron, Mercury/Pyrite),
then Pillar of Mercy (Jupiter/Tin, Venus/Copper, Moon/Silver), finishing with
Sun/Gold at centre.

=== Topics This Week

- Acquiring the seven metals and their practical substitutes
- The meditation protocol: attending, not producing
- Working through the metals by pillar: Severity, Mercy, Centre
- Recording impressions: the metal meditation journal

#inner-work[
  *The Metal Meditation Journal*

  Dedicate a section of your laboratory journal (or Materia Medica) to the
  metal meditations. For each metal, record:
  - Date and duration
  - Physical qualities attended to
  - Quality of awareness or bodily sensation evoked
  - Any images, memories, or associations that arose spontaneously
  - One word that best captures the metal's essential character for you

  The one-word summary is important: it becomes your personal keyword for that
  planetary-metallic force, and will be referenced throughout Year Three.
]

